@2a 2.8 supporting procedures in computer hardware
@2b procedure: a stored subroutine that performs a specifc task
based on provided parameters
@2c execution of a procedure
@2d put params in place
@2e transfer control
@2f acquire resources
@2g perform task
@2h return control
@2i MIPs registers for procedure calling
@2j a0-a3: args
@2k v0-v1: return values
@2l ra: return address
@2m jump-and-link (jal): jumps to an address, saves address of following
instruction in ra, the return address
@2n caller: program that instigates a procedure, provides parameters
@2o callee: procedure, executes sequence of instructions based on caller
params, then returns control to caller
@2p program counter: register containing address of instruction executed
@2q using more registers
@2r stack ideal struct for spilling registers
@2s stack pointer: denotes most recent alloc address that
shows where registers should be spilled / old registers found
@2t historical precedent: stack grows from higher to lower addr
@2u push: achieved via subtracting from stack
pointer
@2v to avoid saving/restoring register whose value is never
used, registers in MIPs are classified as temp (t0-t9) and
saved (s0-s7)
@2w nested procedure
@2x leaf procedure: procedures that do not call other procedures
@2y how to handle register conflicts?
@2z push all preserved registers onto stack
@30 global pointer: register reserved to point to static data, gp
